The paper deals with the implementation of deep Convolutional Neural Networks (ConvNets) on tiny end-nodes with limited non-volatile memory space. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category, as ConvNets are commonly used in computer vision tasks. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel memory-constrained training procedure, which involves pruning and weight encoding, indicating that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also involves optimization techniques, which could place it in the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the deployment of the ConvNet on a low-power microcontroller, which suggests that it could also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
